"""Statistics Canada (StatCan) — universe-first SDMX + WDS client.

Sandbox name: ``statcan_client``.

Statistics Canada publishes the entire Canadian official-statistics
universe (national accounts, prices, labour, trade, government finance,
income/wealth, manufacturing, construction, housing, business
performance, ...) as ~5,000 active CODR cubes (tables), each broken into
elementary time series (vectors). Two public services expose it:

  * WDS REST JSON  (https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/t1/wds/rest)
      - getCodeSets, getAllCubesListLite, getCubeMetadata,
        getSeriesInfoFromVector, getDataFromVectorsAndLatestNPeriods, ...
      - the ONLY way to enumerate / discover cubes (SDMX cannot list
        dataflows).
  * SDMX REST     (https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/t1/wds/sdmx/statcan/rest)
      - data/{DF_<pid>}/{key}, vector/v{id}, structure/Data_Structure_<pid>
      - the standards-based data-retrieval surface (the user-facing spec).

This client is organised around PROGRESSIVE DISCLOSURE so PRISM can reach
the full universe without memorising PIDs:

  L1  this module's signature + triggers (always-on).
  L2  the embedded ontology — subject taxonomy + code sets + a cube index
      of every active cube (title, subjects, frequency, coverage). Query
      it offline to find the right table BEFORE any network call.
  L3  on-demand cube structure — get_cube_metadata(pid) fetches the live
      DSD (dimensions + members) for any cube, including archived ones not
      in the embedded index.
  L4  data — get_vector(vectors) / query(pid, **dims) return clean, coerced
      series dicts. Retrieval goes through WDS (reliable refPer/value per
      point); get_data_sdmx() is the raw SDMX REST escape hatch and
      get_full_table_url() returns the bulk CSV/SDMX download.

StatCan SDMX-JSON quirks the wrapper absorbs so PRISM never sees them:
TIME_PERIOD ids are mislabelled (periods derived from the ISO start +
frequency) and multi-series observations use a global index. WDS is used
for retrieval because it is free of these quirks.

The embedded ontology is baked from the last refresh_ontology() run.
refresh_ontology(write_to=__file__) re-harvests it (offline tool — never
called from the PRISM sandbox).

Transport: Bucket A — session_and_auth() (standard requests + GS Kerberos
proxy adapter in PRISM; vanilla requests through the staging stub mirror).
"""

from __future__ import annotations

import json
import re
import unicodedata
from typing import Any, Dict, List, Optional, Sequence, Tuple, Union

import requests

from ai_development.mcp.gs_app_proxy_negotiate import session_and_auth


# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Constants
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------

WDS_BASE = "https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/t1/wds/rest"
SDMX_BASE = "https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/t1/wds/sdmx/statcan/rest"

# Specific SDMX mime types (the user guide strongly recommends these over
# the generic application/json, which floats to the newest format version).
SDMX_JSON_ACCEPT = "application/vnd.sdmx.data+json;version=1.0.0-wd"

DEFAULT_TIMEOUT = 60

# StatCan archive status: "2" = active/current, "1" = archived/discontinued.
ARCHIVE_ACTIVE = "2"

# The 11 subject domains that make up the Canadian macro / financial /
# economic universe. cubes_by_subject / the L2 guide emphasise these; the
# embedded cube index covers ALL active subjects, and get_cube_metadata
# reaches archived cubes too.
MACRO_SUBJECTS = ("10", "11", "12", "14", "16", "18", "20", "33", "34", "36", "46")


class StatCanError(Exception):
    """Raised on StatCan WDS/SDMX request or validation failure."""


